# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: great-expectations-deep
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:great-expectations-deep/data-pipeline] In computing, a **pipeline**, also known as a **data pipeline**, is a set of data processing elements connected in series, where the output of one element is the input of the next one.
[src:great-expectations-deep/data-pipeline] The elements of a pipeline are often executed in parallel or in time-sliced fashion.
[src:great-expectations-deep/data-pipeline] Some amount of buffer storage is often inserted between elements.
[src:great-expectations-deep/data-pipeline] Pipelining is a commonly used concept in everyday life.
[src:great-expectations-deep/data-pipeline] For example, in the assembly line of a car factory, each specific task—such as installing the engine, installing the hood, and installing the wheels—is often done by a separate work station.
[src:great-expectations-deep/data-pipeline] The stations carry out their tasks in parallel, each on a different car.
[src:great-expectations-deep/data-pipeline] Once a car has had one task performed, it moves to the next station.
[src:great-expectations-deep/data-pipeline] Variations in the time needed to complete the tasks can be accommodated by "buffering" (holding one or more cars in a space between the stations) and/or by "stalling" (temporarily halting the upstream stations), until the next station becomes available.
[src:great-expectations-deep/data-pipeline] Suppose that assembling one car requires three tasks that take 20, 10, and 15 minutes, respectively.
[src:great-expectations-deep/data-pipeline] Then, if all three tasks were performed by a single station, the factory would output one car every 45 minutes.
[src:great-expectations-deep/data-pipeline] By using a pipeline of three stations, the factory would output the first car in 45 minutes, and then a new one every 20 minutes.
[src:great-expectations-deep/data-pipeline] As this example shows, pipelining does not decrease the latency, that is, the total time for one item to go through the whole system.
[src:great-expectations-deep/data-pipeline] It does however increase the system's throughput, that is, the rate at which new items are processed after the first one.
[src:great-expectations-deep/data-pipeline] In computing, a pipeline or data pipeline is a set of data processing elements connected in series, where the output of one element is the input of the next one.
[src:great-expectations-deep/data-pipeline] If a pipeline consists of idempotent steps, these can be rerun without altering the outcome beyond the initial run.
[src:great-expectations-deep/data-pipeline] This is advantageous in terms of reliability and maintenance.
[src:great-expectations-deep/data-pipeline] Since the throughput of a pipeline cannot be better than that of its slowest element, the designer should try to divide the work and resources among the stages so that they all take the same time to complete their tasks.
[src:great-expectations-deep/data-pipeline] In the car assembly example above, if the three tasks took 15 minutes each, instead of 20, 10, and 15 minutes, the latency would still be 45 minutes, but a new car would then be finished every 15 minutes, instead of 20.
[src:great-expectations-deep/data-pipeline] Under ideal circumstances, if all processing elements are synchronized and take the same amount of time to process, then each item can be received by each element just as it is released by the previous one, in a single clock cycle.
[src:great-expectations-deep/data-pipeline] That way, the items will flow through the pipeline at a constant speed, like waves in a water channel.
[src:great-expectations-deep/data-pipeline] In such "wave pipelines", no synchronization or buffering is needed between the stages, besides the storage needed for the data items.
[src:great-expectations-deep/data-pipeline] More generally, buffering between the pipeline stages is necessary when the processing times are irregular, or when items may be created or destroyed along the pipeline.
[src:great-expectations-deep/data-pipeline] For example, in a graphics pipeline that processes triangles to be rendered on the screen, an element that checks the visibility of each triangle may discard the triangle if it is invisible, or may output two or more triangular pieces of the element if they are partly hidden.
[src:great-expectations-deep/data-pipeline] Buffering is also needed to accommodate irregularities in the rates at which the application feeds items to the first stage and consumes the output of the last one.
[src:great-expectations-deep/data-pipeline] The buffer between two stages may be simply a hardware register with suitable synchronization and signalling logic between the two stages.
[src:great-expectations-deep/data-pipeline] When a stage A stores a data item in the register, it sends a "data available" signal to the next stage B.
[src:great-expectations-deep/data-pipeline] Once B has used that data, it responds with a "data received" signal to A.
[src:great-expectations-deep/data-pipeline] Stage A halts, waiting for this signal, before storing the next data item into the register.
[src:great-expectations-deep/data-pipeline] Stage B halts, waiting for the "data available" signal, if it is ready to process the next item but stage A has not provided it yet.
[src:great-expectations-deep/data-pipeline] If the processing times of an element are variable, the whole pipeline may often have to stop, waiting for that element and all the previous ones to consume the items in their input buffers.
[src:great-expectations-deep/data-pipeline] The frequency of such pipeline stalls can be reduced by providing space for more than one item in the input buffer of that stage.
[src:great-expectations-deep/data-pipeline] Such a multiple-item buffer is usually implemented as a first-in, first-out queue.
[src:great-expectations-deep/data-pipeline] The upstream stage may still have to be halted when the queue gets full, but the frequency of those events will decrease as more buffer slots are provided.
[src:great-expectations-deep/data-pipeline] Queueing theory can tell the number of buffer slots needed, depending on the variability of the processing times and on the desired performance.
[src:great-expectations-deep/data-pipeline] If some stage takes (or may take) much longer than the others, and cannot be sped up, the designer can provide two or more processing elements to carry out that task in parallel, with a single input buffer and a single output buffer.
[src:great-expectations-deep/data-pipeline] As each element finishes processing its current data item, it delivers it to the common output buffer, and takes the next data item from the common input buffer.
[src:great-expectations-deep/data-pipeline] This concept of "non-linear" or "dynamic" pipeline is exemplified by shops or banks that have two or more cashiers serving clients from a single waiting queue.
[src:great-expectations-deep/data-pipeline] In some applications, the processing of an item Y by a stage A may depend on the results or effect of processing a previous item X by some later stage B of the pipeline.
[src:great-expectations-deep/data-pipeline] In that case, stage A cannot correctly process item Y until item X has cleared stage B.
[src:great-expectations-deep/data-pipeline] This situation occurs very often in instruction pipelines.
[src:great-expectations-deep/data-pipeline] For example, suppose that Y is an arithmetic instruction that reads the contents of a register that was supposed to have been modified by an earlier instruction X.
[src:great-expectations-deep/data-pipeline] Let A be the stage that fetches the instruction operands, and B be the stage that writes the result to the specified register.
[src:great-expectations-deep/data-pipeline] If stage A tries to process instruction Y before instruction X reaches stage B, the register may still contain the old value, and the effect of Y would be incorrect.
[src:great-expectations-deep/data-pipeline] In order to handle such conflicts correctly, the pipeline must be provided with extra circuitry or logic that detects them and takes the appropriate action.
[src:great-expectations-deep/data-pipeline] Rather than halt while waiting for X to be finished, stage A may guess whether the branch will be taken or not, and fetch the next instruction Y based on that guess.
[src:great-expectations-deep/data-pipeline] If the guess later turns out to be incorrect (hopefully rarely), the system would have to backtrack and resume with the correct choice.
[src:great-expectations-deep/data-pipeline] To be effectively implemented, data pipelines need a CPU scheduling strategy to dispatch work to the available CPU cores, and the usage of data structures on which the pipeline stages will operate on.
[src:great-expectations-deep/data-pipeline] For example, UNIX derivatives may pipeline commands connecting various processes' standard IO, using the pipes implemented by the operating system.
[src:great-expectations-deep/data-pipeline] Some operating systems may provide UNIX-like syntax to string several program runs in a pipeline, but implement the latter as simple serial execution, rather than true pipelining—namely, by waiting for each program to finish before starting the next one.
[src:great-expectations-deep/data-pipeline] Lower level approaches may rely on the threads provided by the operating system to schedule work on the stages: both thread pool-based implementations or on a one-thread-per-stage are viable, and exist.
[src:great-expectations-deep/data-pipeline] Other strategies relying on cooperative multitasking exist, that do not need multiple threads of execution and hence additional CPU cores, such as using a round-robin scheduler with a coroutine-based framework.
[src:great-expectations-deep/data-pipeline] In this context, each stage may be instantiated with its own coroutine, yielding control back to the scheduler after finishing its round task.
[src:great-expectations-deep/data-pipeline] This approach may need careful control over the process' stages to avoid them abuse their time slice.
[src:great-expectations-deep/data-pipeline] A pipelined system typically requires more resources (circuit elements, processing units, computer memory, etc.) than one that executes one batch at a time, because its stages cannot share those resources, and because buffering and additional synchronization logic may be needed between the elements.
[src:great-expectations-deep/data-pipeline] Moreover, the transfer of items between separate processing elements may increase the latency, especially for long pipelines.
[src:great-expectations-deep/data-pipeline] The additional complexity cost of pipelining may be considerable if there are dependencies between the processing of different items, especially if a guess-and-backtrack strategy is used to handle them.
[src:great-expectations-deep/data-pipeline] Indeed, the cost of implementing that strategy for complex instruction sets has motivated some radical proposals to simplify computer architecture, such as RISC and VLIW.
[src:great-expectations-deep/data-pipeline] Compilers also have been burdened with the task of rearranging the machine instructions so as to improve the performance of instruction pipelines.
[src:great-expectations-deep/data-pipeline] In recent years the demands on applications and their underlying hardware have been significant.
[src:great-expectations-deep/data-pipeline] For example, building pipelines with single node applications that trawl through the data row by row is no longer feasible with the volume and variety of big data.
[src:great-expectations-deep/data-pipeline] However, with the advent of data analytics engines such as Hadoop, or more recently Apache Spark, it's been possible to distribute large datasets across multiple processing nodes, allowing applications to reach heights of efficiency several hundred times greater than was thought possible before.
[src:great-expectations-deep/data-pipeline] The effect of this today is that even a mid-level PC using distributed processing in this fashion can handle the building and running of big data pipelines.
[src:great-expectations-deep/data-quality] People's views on data quality can often be in disagreement, even when discussing the same set of data used for the same purpose.
[src:great-expectations-deep/data-quality] When this is the case, businesses may adopt recognised international standards for data quality (See #International Standards for Data Quality below).
[src:great-expectations-deep/data-quality] Data governance can also be used to form agreed upon definitions and standards, including international standards, for data quality.
[src:great-expectations-deep/data-quality] In such cases, data cleansing, including standardization, may be required in order to ensure data quality.
[src:great-expectations-deep/data-quality] Defining data quality is difficult due to the many contexts data are used in, as well as the varying perspectives among end users, producers, and custodians of data.
[src:great-expectations-deep/data-quality] A systematic scoping review of the literature suggests that data quality dimensions and methods with real world data are not consistent in the literature, and as a result quality assessments are challenging due to the complex and heterogeneous nature of these data.
[src:great-expectations-deep/data-quality] ISO 8000 is an international standard for data quality.
[src:great-expectations-deep/data-quality] Before the rise of the inexpensive computer data storage, massive mainframe computers were used to maintain name and address data for delivery services.
[src:great-expectations-deep/data-quality] This was so that mail could be properly routed to its destination.
[src:great-expectations-deep/data-quality] The mainframes used business rules to correct common misspellings and typographical errors in name and address data, as well as to track customers who had moved, died, gone to prison, married, divorced, or experienced other life-changing events.
[src:great-expectations-deep/data-quality] Government agencies began to make postal data available to a few service companies to cross-reference customer data with the National Change of Address registry (NCOA).
[src:great-expectations-deep/data-quality] This technology saved large companies millions of dollars in comparison to manual correction of customer data.
[src:great-expectations-deep/data-quality] Large companies saved on postage, as bills and direct marketing materials made their way to the intended customer more accurately.
[src:great-expectations-deep/data-quality] Initially sold as a service, data quality moved inside the walls of corporations, as low-cost and powerful server technology became available.
[src:great-expectations-deep/data-quality] Companies with an emphasis on marketing often focused their quality efforts on name and address information, but data quality is recognized as an important property of all types of data.
[src:great-expectations-deep/data-quality] Principles of data quality can be applied to supply chain data, transactional data, and nearly every other category of data found.
[src:great-expectations-deep/data-quality] For companies with significant research efforts, data quality can include developing protocols for research methods, reducing measurement error, bounds checking of data, cross tabulation, modeling and outlier detection, verifying data integrity, etc.
[src:great-expectations-deep/data-quality] There are a number of theoretical frameworks for understanding data quality.
[src:great-expectations-deep/data-quality] A systems-theoretical approach influenced by American pragmatism expands the definition of data quality to include information quality, and emphasizes the inclusiveness of the fundamental dimensions of accuracy and precision on the basis of the theory of science (Ivanov, 1972).
[src:great-expectations-deep/data-quality] One framework, dubbed "Zero Defect Data" (Hansen, 1991) adapts the principles of statistical process control to data quality.
[src:great-expectations-deep/data-quality] Another framework seeks to integrate the product perspective (conformance to specifications) and the service perspective (meeting consumers' expectations) (Kahn et al.
[src:great-expectations-deep/data-quality] Another framework is based in semiotics to evaluate the quality of the form, meaning and use of the data (Price and Shanks, 2004).
[src:great-expectations-deep/data-quality] One highly theoretical approach analyzes the ontological nature of information systems to define data quality rigorously (Wand and Wang, 1996).
[src:great-expectations-deep/data-quality] A considerable amount of data quality research involves investigating and describing various categories of desirable attributes (or dimensions) of data.
[src:great-expectations-deep/data-quality] Nearly 200 such terms have been identified and there is little agreement in their nature (are these concepts, goals or criteria?), their definitions or measures (Wang et al., 1993).
[src:great-expectations-deep/data-quality] Software engineers may recognize this as a similar problem to "ilities".
[src:great-expectations-deep/data-quality] MIT has an Information Quality (MITIQ) Program, led by Professor Richard Wang, which produces a large number of publications and hosts a significant international conference in this field (International Conference on Information Quality, ICIQ).
[src:great-expectations-deep/data-quality] This program grew out of the work done by Hansen on the "Zero Defect Data" framework (Hansen, 1991).
[src:great-expectations-deep/data-quality] In practice, data quality is a concern for professionals involved with a wide range of information systems, ranging from data warehousing and business intelligence to customer relationship management and supply chain management.
[src:great-expectations-deep/data-quality] One industry study estimated the total cost to the U.S. economy of data quality problems at over U.S. $600 billion per annum (Eckerson, 2002).
[src:great-expectations-deep/data-quality] Incorrect data – which includes invalid and outdated information – can originate from different data sources – through data entry, or data migration and conversion projects.
[src:great-expectations-deep/data-quality] In 2002, the USPS and PricewaterhouseCoopers released a report stating that 23.6 percent of all U.S. mail sent is incorrectly addressed.
[src:great-expectations-deep/data-quality] One reason contact data becomes stale very quickly in the average database – more than 45 million Americans change their address every year.
[src:great-expectations-deep/data-quality] In fact, the problem is such a concern that companies are beginning to set up a data governance team whose sole role in the corporation is to be responsible for data quality.
[src:great-expectations-deep/data-quality] In some organizations, this data governance function has been established as part of a larger Regulatory Compliance function - a recognition of the importance of Data/Information Quality to organizations.
[src:great-expectations-deep/data-quality] Problems with data quality don't only arise from *incorrect* data; *inconsistent* data is a problem as well.
[src:great-expectations-deep/data-quality] Eliminating data shadow systems and centralizing data in a warehouse is one of the initiatives a company can take to ensure data consistency.
[src:great-expectations-deep/data-quality] Enterprises, scientists, and researchers are starting to participate within data curation communities to improve the quality of their common data.
[src:great-expectations-deep/data-quality] The market is going some way to providing data quality assurance.
[src:great-expectations-deep/data-quality] A number of vendors make tools for analyzing and repairing poor quality data *in situ*, service providers can clean the data on a contract basis and consultants can advise on fixing processes or systems to avoid data quality problems in the first place.
[src:great-expectations-deep/data-quality] Matching or Linking - a way to compare data so that similar, but slightly different records can be aligned.
[src:great-expectations-deep/data-quality] Matching may use "fuzzy logic" to find duplicates in the data.
[src:great-expectations-deep/data-quality] It often recognizes that "Bob" and "Bbo" may be the same individual.
[src:great-expectations-deep/data-quality] It might be able to manage "householding", or finding links between spouses at the same address, for example.
[src:great-expectations-deep/data-quality] Finally, it often can build a "best of breed" record, taking the best components from multiple data sources and building a single super-record.
[src:great-expectations-deep/data-quality] Monitoring - keeping track of data quality over time and reporting variations in the quality of data.
[src:great-expectations-deep/data-quality] Software can also auto-correct the variations based on pre-defined business rules.
[src:great-expectations-deep/data-quality] Batch and Real time - Once the data is initially cleansed (batch), companies often want to build the processes into enterprise applications to keep it clean.
[src:great-expectations-deep/data-quality] Data quality assurance is the process of data profiling to discover inconsistencies and other anomalies in the data, as well as performing data cleansing activities (e.g. removing outliers, missing data interpolation) to improve the data quality.
[src:great-expectations-deep/data-quality] These activities can be undertaken as part of data warehousing or as part of the database administration of an existing piece of application software.
[src:great-expectations-deep/data-quality] The Data QC process uses the information from the QA process to decide to use the data for analysis or in an application or business process.
[src:great-expectations-deep/data-quality] General example: if a Data QC process finds that the data contains too many errors or inconsistencies, then it prevents that data from being used for its intended process which could cause disruption.
[src:great-expectations-deep/data-quality] Specific example: providing invalid measurements from several sensors to the automatic pilot feature on an aircraft could cause it to crash.
[src:great-expectations-deep/data-quality] Thus, establishing a QC process provides data usage protection.
[src:great-expectations-deep/data-quality] Data Quality (DQ) is a niche area required for the integrity of the data management by covering gaps of data issues.
[src:great-expectations-deep/data-quality] This is one of the key functions that aid data governance by monitoring data to find exceptions undiscovered by current data management operations.
[src:great-expectations-deep/data-quality] Data Quality checks may be defined at attribute level to have full control on its remediation steps.
[src:great-expectations-deep/data-quality] DQ checks and business rules may easily overlap if an organization is not attentive of its DQ scope.
[src:great-expectations-deep/data-quality] Business teams should understand the DQ scope thoroughly in order to avoid overlap.
[src:great-expectations-deep/data-quality] Data quality checks are redundant if **business logic** covers the same functionality and fulfills the same purpose as DQ.
[src:great-expectations-deep/data-quality] The DQ scope of an organization should be defined in DQ strategy and well implemented.
[src:great-expectations-deep/data-quality] Some data quality checks may be translated into business rules after repeated instances of exceptions in the past.
[src:great-expectations-deep/data-quality] All data having attributes referring to *Reference Data* in the organization may be validated against the set of well-defined valid values of Reference Data to discover new or discrepant values through the **validity** DQ check.
[src:great-expectations-deep/data-quality] Results may be used to update *Reference Data* administered under *Master Data Management (MDM)*.
[src:great-expectations-deep/data-quality] All data sourced from a *third party* to organization's internal teams may undergo **accuracy** (DQ) check against the third party data.
[src:great-expectations-deep/data-quality] These DQ check results are valuable when administered on data that made multiple hops after the point of entry of that data but before that data becomes authorized or stored for enterprise intelligence.
[src:great-expectations-deep/data-quality] All data columns that refer to *Master Data* may be validated for its **consistency** check.
[src:great-expectations-deep/data-quality] A DQ check administered on the data at the point of entry discovers new data for the MDM process, but a DQ check administered after the point of entry discovers the failure (not exceptions) of consistency.
[src:great-expectations-deep/data-quality] As data transforms, multiple timestamps and the positions of that timestamps are captured and may be compared against each other and its leeway to validate its value, decay, operational significance against a defined SLA (service level agreement).
[src:great-expectations-deep/data-quality] This **timeliness** DQ check can be utilized to decrease data value decay rate and optimize the policies of data movement timeline.
[src:great-expectations-deep/data-quality] In an organization complex logic is usually segregated into simpler logic across multiple processes.
[src:great-expectations-deep/data-quality] This check may be a simple generic aggregation rule engulfed by large chunk of data or it can be a complicated logic on a group of attributes of a transaction pertaining to the core business of the organization.
[src:great-expectations-deep/data-quality] This DQ check requires high degree of business knowledge and acumen.
[src:great-expectations-deep/data-quality] Discovery of reasonableness issues may aid for policy and strategy changes by either business or data governance or both.
[src:great-expectations-deep/data-quality] There are many places in the data movement where DQ checks may not be required.
[src:great-expectations-deep/data-quality] For instance, DQ check for completeness and precision on not–null columns is redundant for the data sourced from database.
[src:great-expectations-deep/data-quality] Similarly, data should be validated for its accuracy with respect to time when the data is stitched across disparate sources.
[src:great-expectations-deep/data-quality] However, that is a business rule and should not be in the DQ scope.
[src:great-expectations-deep/data-quality] Regretfully, from a software development perspective, DQ is often seen as a nonfunctional requirement.
[src:great-expectations-deep/data-quality] And as such, key data quality checks/processes are not factored into the final software solution.
[src:great-expectations-deep/data-quality] Within healthcare, wearable technologies or Body Area Networks, generate large volumes of data.
[src:great-expectations-deep/data-quality] The level of detail required to ensure data quality is extremely high and is often underestimated.
[src:great-expectations-deep/data-quality] This is also true for the vast majority of mHealth apps, EHRs and other health related software solutions.
[src:great-expectations-deep/data-quality] However, some open source tools exist that examine data quality.
[src:great-expectations-deep/data-quality] The primary reason for this, stems from the extra cost involved is added a higher degree of rigor within the software architecture.
[src:great-expectations-deep/data-quality] The use of mobile devices in health, or mHealth, creates new challenges to health data security and privacy, in ways that directly affect data quality. mHealth is an increasingly important strategy for delivery of health services in low- and middle-income countries.
[src:great-expectations-deep/data-quality] Mobile phones and tablets are used for collection, reporting, and analysis of data in near real time.
[src:great-expectations-deep/data-quality] However, these mobile devices are commonly used for personal activities, as well, leaving them more vulnerable to security risks that could lead to data breaches.
[src:great-expectations-deep/data-quality] Without proper security safeguards, this personal use could jeopardize the quality, security, and confidentiality of health data.
[src:great-expectations-deep/data-quality] Data quality has become a major focus of public health programs in recent years, especially as demand for accountability increases.
[src:great-expectations-deep/data-quality] Work towards ambitious goals related to the fight against diseases such as AIDS, Tuberculosis, and Malaria must be predicated on strong Monitoring and Evaluation systems that produce quality data related to program implementation.
[src:great-expectations-deep/data-quality] These programs, and program auditors, increasingly seek tools to standardize and streamline the process of determining the quality of data, verify the quality of reported data, and assess the underlying data management and reporting systems for indicators.
[src:great-expectations-deep/data-quality] An example is WHO and MEASURE Evaluation's Data Quality Review Tool WHO, the Global Fund, GAVI, and MEASURE Evaluation have collaborated to produce a harmonized approach to data quality assurance across different diseases and programs.
[src:great-expectations-deep/data-quality] There are a number of scientific works devoted to the analysis of the data quality in open data sources, such as Wikipedia, Wikidata, DBpedia and other.
[src:great-expectations-deep/data-quality] In the case of Wikipedia, quality analysis may relate to the whole article Modeling of quality there is carried out by means of various methods.
[src:great-expectations-deep/data-quality] Some of them use machine learning algorithms, including Random Forest, Support Vector Machine, and others.
[src:great-expectations-deep/data-quality] Methods for assessing data quality in Wikidata, DBpedia and other LOD sources differ.
[src:great-expectations-deep/data-quality] The Electronic Commerce Code Management Association (ECCMA) is a member-based, international not-for-profit association committed to improving data quality through the implementation of international standards.
[src:great-expectations-deep/data-quality] ECCMA is the current project leader for the development of ISO 8000 and ISO 22745, which are the international standards for data quality and the exchange of material and service master data, respectively.
[src:great-expectations-deep/data-quality] ECCMA provides a platform for collaboration amongst subject experts on data quality and data governance around the world to build and maintain global, open standard dictionaries that are used to unambiguously label information.
[src:great-expectations-deep/data-quality] The existence of these dictionaries (known as Open Technical Dictionaries) of labels (acting as metadata and reference data) allows information to be passed from one computer system to another without losing meaning.
[src:great-expectations-deep/data-validation] In computing, **data validation** or **input validation** is the process of ensuring data has undergone data cleansing to confirm it has data quality, that is, that it is both correct and useful.
[src:great-expectations-deep/data-validation] It uses routines, often called "validation rules", "validation constraints", or "check routines", that check for correctness, meaningfulness, and security of data that are input to the system.
[src:great-expectations-deep/data-validation] The rules may be implemented through the automated facilities of a data dictionary, or by the inclusion of explicit application program validation logic of the computer and its application.
[src:great-expectations-deep/data-validation] This is distinct from formal verification, which attempts to prove or disprove the correctness of algorithms for implementing a specification or property.
[src:great-expectations-deep/data-validation] Data validation is intended to provide certain well-defined guarantees for fitness and consistency of data in an application or automated system.
[src:great-expectations-deep/data-validation] Data validation rules can be defined and designed using various methodologies, and be deployed in various contexts.
[src:great-expectations-deep/data-validation] Their implementation can use declarative data integrity rules, or procedure-based business rules.
[src:great-expectations-deep/data-validation] The guarantees of data validation do not necessarily include accuracy, and it is possible for data entry errors such as misspellings to be accepted as valid.
[src:great-expectations-deep/data-validation] Other clerical and/or computer controls may be applied to reduce inaccuracy within a system.
[src:great-expectations-deep/data-validation] In evaluating the basics of data validation, generalizations can be made regarding the different kinds of validation according to their scope, complexity, and purpose.
[src:great-expectations-deep/data-validation] Data type validation is customarily carried out on one or more simple data fields.
[src:great-expectations-deep/data-validation] The simplest kind of data type validation verifies that the individual characters provided through user input are consistent with the expected characters of one or more known primitive data types as defined in a programming language or data storage and retrieval mechanism.
[src:great-expectations-deep/data-validation] For example, an integer field may require input to use only characters 0 through 9.
[src:great-expectations-deep/data-validation] Simple range and constraint validation may examine input for consistency with a minimum/maximum range, or consistency with a test for evaluating a sequence of characters, such as one or more tests against regular expressions.
[src:great-expectations-deep/data-validation] For example, a counter value may be required to be a non-negative integer, and a password may be required to meet a minimum length and contain characters from multiple categories.
[src:great-expectations-deep/data-validation] Code and cross-reference validation includes operations to verify that data is consistent with one or more possibly-external rules, requirements, or collections relevant to a particular organization, context or set of underlying assumptions.
[src:great-expectations-deep/data-validation] These additional validity constraints may involve cross-referencing supplied data with a known look-up table or directory information service such as LDAP.
[src:great-expectations-deep/data-validation] For example, a user-provided country code might be required to identify a current geopolitical region.
[src:great-expectations-deep/data-validation] Structured validation allows for the combination of other kinds of validation, along with more complex processing.
[src:great-expectations-deep/data-validation] Such complex processing may include the testing of conditional constraints for an entire complex data object or set of process operations within a system.
[src:great-expectations-deep/data-validation] Consistency validation ensures that data is logical.
[src:great-expectations-deep/data-validation] For example, the delivery date of an order can be prohibited from preceding its shipment date.
[src:great-expectations-deep/data-validation] Multiple kinds of data validation are relevant to 10-digit pre-2007 ISBNs (the 2005 edition of ISO 2108 required ISBNs to have 13 digits from 2007 onwards).
[src:great-expectations-deep/data-validation] Checks to ascertain that only expected characters are present in a field.
[src:great-expectations-deep/data-validation] For example a numeric field may only allow the digits 0–9, the decimal point and perhaps a minus sign or commas.
[src:great-expectations-deep/data-validation] An e-mail address might require at least one @ sign and various other structural details.
[src:great-expectations-deep/data-validation] can be effective ways to implement such checks.
[src:great-expectations-deep/data-validation] Numerical fields may be added together for all records in a batch.
[src:great-expectations-deep/data-validation] The batch total is entered and the computer checks that the total is correct, e.g., add the 'Total Cost' field of a number of transactions together.
[src:great-expectations-deep/data-validation] Checks that record has a valid number of related records.
[src:great-expectations-deep/data-validation] For example, if a contact record is classified as "customer" then it must have at least one associated order (cardinality > 0).
[src:great-expectations-deep/data-validation] This type of rule can be complicated by additional conditions.
[src:great-expectations-deep/data-validation] For example, if a contact record in a payroll database is classified as "former employee" then it must not have any associated salary payments after the separation date (cardinality = 0).
[src:great-expectations-deep/data-validation] To support error detection, an extra digit is added to a number which is calculated from the other digits.
[src:great-expectations-deep/data-validation] Checks fields to ensure data in these fields correspond, e.g., if expiration date is in the past then status is not "active".
[src:great-expectations-deep/data-validation] Compares data in different systems to ensure it is consistent.
[src:great-expectations-deep/data-validation] Systems may represent the same data differently, in which case comparison requires transformation (e.g., one system may store customer name in a single Name field as 'Doe, John Q', while another uses First_Name 'John' and Last_Name 'Doe' and Middle_Name 'Quality').
[src:great-expectations-deep/data-validation] Checks input conformance with typed data.
[src:great-expectations-deep/data-validation] For example, an input box accepting numeric data may reject the letter 'O'.
[src:great-expectations-deep/data-validation] Checks that a file with a specified name exists.
[src:great-expectations-deep/data-validation] This check is essential for programs that use file handling.
[src:great-expectations-deep/data-validation] Checks that the data is in a specified format (template), e.g., dates have to be in the format YYYY-MM-DD.
[src:great-expectations-deep/data-validation] Regular expressions may be used for this kind of validation.
[src:great-expectations-deep/data-validation] Checks that data is present, e.g., customers may be required to have an email address.
[src:great-expectations-deep/data-validation] Checks that the data is within a specified range of values, e.g., a probability must be between 0 and 1.
[src:great-expectations-deep/data-validation] tables can be linked through foreign key and primary key.
[src:great-expectations-deep/data-validation] If values in the foreign key field are not constrained by internal mechanisms, then they should be validated to ensure that the referencing table always refers to a row in the referenced table.
[src:great-expectations-deep/data-validation] Looks for spelling and grammatical errors.
[src:great-expectations-deep/data-validation] This can be applied to several fields (i.e.
[src:great-expectations-deep/data-validation] A table look up check compares data to a collection of allowed values.
[src:great-expectations-deep/data-validation] Enforcement action typically rejects the data entry request and requires the input actor to make a change that brings the data into compliance.
[src:great-expectations-deep/data-validation] This is most suitable for interactive use, where a real person is sitting on the computer and making entry.
[src:great-expectations-deep/data-validation] It also works well for batch upload, where a file input may be rejected and a set of messages sent back to the input source for why the data is rejected.
[src:great-expectations-deep/data-validation] Another form of enforcement action involves automatically changing the data and saving a conformant version instead of the original version.
[src:great-expectations-deep/data-validation] This is most suitable for cosmetic change.
[src:great-expectations-deep/data-validation] For example, converting an [all-caps] entry to a [Pascal case] entry does not need user input.
[src:great-expectations-deep/data-validation] An inappropriate use of automatic enforcement would be in situations where the enforcement leads to loss of business information.
[src:great-expectations-deep/data-validation] For example, saving a truncated comment if the length is longer than expected.
[src:great-expectations-deep/data-validation] This is not typically a good thing since it may result in loss of significant data.
[src:great-expectations-deep/data-validation] Advisory actions typically allow data to be entered unchanged but sends a message to the source actor indicating those validation issues that were encountered.
[src:great-expectations-deep/data-validation] This is most suitable for non-interactive system, for systems where the change is not business critical, for cleansing steps of existing data and for verification steps of an entry process.
[src:great-expectations-deep/data-validation] Verification actions are special cases of advisory actions.
[src:great-expectations-deep/data-validation] In this case, the source actor is asked to verify that this data is what they would really want to enter, in the light of a suggestion to the contrary.
[src:great-expectations-deep/data-validation] Here, the check step suggests an alternative (e.g., a check of a mailing address returns a different way of formatting that address or suggests a different address altogether).
[src:great-expectations-deep/data-validation] You would want in this case, to give the user the option of accepting the recommendation or keeping their version.
[src:great-expectations-deep/data-validation] This is not a strict validation process, by design and is useful for capturing addresses to a new location or to a location that is not yet supported by the validation databases.
[src:great-expectations-deep/data-validation] Even in cases where data validation did not find any issues, providing a log of validations that were conducted and their results is important.
[src:great-expectations-deep/data-validation] Failures or omissions in data validation can lead to data corruption or a security vulnerability.
[src:great-expectations-deep/data-validation] Data validation checks that data are fit for purpose, valid, sensible, reasonable and secure before they are processed.
[src:great-expectations-deep/develop-readme-md] GX Core combines the collective wisdom of thousands of community members with a proven track record in data quality deployments worldwide, wrapped into a super-simple package for data teams.
[src:great-expectations-deep/develop-readme-md] Its powerful technical tools start with Expectations: expressive and extensible unit tests for your data.
[src:great-expectations-deep/develop-readme-md] Expectations foster collaboration by giving teams a common language to express data quality tests in an intuitive way.
[src:great-expectations-deep/develop-readme-md] You can automatically generate documentation for each set of validation results, making it easy for everyone to stay on the same page.
[src:great-expectations-deep/develop-readme-md] This not only simplifies your data quality processes, but helps preserve your organization’s institutional knowledge about its data.
[src:great-expectations-deep/develop-readme-md] Learn more about how data teams are using GX Core in our featured case studies.
[src:great-expectations-deep/develop-readme-md] Experimental support for Python `3.14` and later can be enabled by setting a `GX_PYTHON_EXPERIMENTAL` environment variable when installing `great_expectations`.
[src:great-expectations-deep/develop-readme-md] For data sources and other integrations that GX supports, see the compatibility reference for additional information.
[src:great-expectations-deep/develop-readme-md] GX recommends deploying GX Core within a virtual environment.
[src:great-expectations-deep/develop-readme-md] For more information about getting started with GX Core, see Introduction to GX Core.
[src:great-expectations-deep/develop-readme-md] We truly value the contributions of our community and always welcome pull requests.
[src:great-expectations-deep/develop-readme-md] PRs are encouraged for both bug fixes and new features.
[src:great-expectations-deep/develop-readme-md] For feature requests, we ask that you first open an issue for discussion to ensure the feature fits within the vision for GX Core and to align on the approach so that your time and effort are well spent.
[src:great-expectations-deep/develop-readme-md] Thank you for being a crucial part of GX Core!
[src:great-expectations-deep/develop-readme-md] Everyone interacting in GX Core project codebases, Discourse forums, Slack channels, and email communications is expected to adhere to the GX Community Code of Conduct.
[src:great-expectations-deep/home] Get started with the Great Expectations Python library.
[src:great-expectations-deep/home] Use tutorials and conceptual topics to learn more about GX features and functionality.
[src:great-expectations-deep/home] View API reference for details on classes and methods.
[src:great-expectations-deep/software-testing-p01] Software testing can provide objective, independent information about the quality of software and the risk of its failure to a user or sponsor or any other stakeholder.
[src:great-expectations-deep/software-testing-p01] Software testing can determine the correctness of software for specific scenarios but cannot determine correctness for all scenarios.
[src:great-expectations-deep/software-testing-p01] Based on the criteria for measuring correctness from an oracle, software testing employs principles and mechanisms that might recognize a problem.
[src:great-expectations-deep/software-testing-p01] Examples of oracles include specifications, contracts, comparable products, past versions of the same product, inferences about intended or expected purpose, user or customer expectations, relevant standards, and applicable laws.
[src:great-expectations-deep/software-testing-p01] Software testing can be functional or non-functional in nature.
[src:great-expectations-deep/software-testing-p01] Software testing is often dynamic in nature: running the software to verify actual output matches expected.
[src:great-expectations-deep/software-testing-p01] It can also be static in nature: reviewing code and its associated documentation.
[src:great-expectations-deep/software-testing-p01] Software testing is often used to answer the question: Does the software do what it is supposed to do and what it needs to do?
[src:great-expectations-deep/software-testing-p01] Information learned from software testing may be used to improve the process by which software is developed.
[src:great-expectations-deep/software-testing-p01] A commonly suggested approach to automated testing is the "test pyramid," wherein most of the tests are unit tests, followed by a smaller set of integration tests and finally a few end-to-end (e2e) tests.
[src:great-expectations-deep/software-testing-p01] A study conducted by NIST in 2002 reported that software bugs cost the U.S. economy $59.5 billion annually.
[src:great-expectations-deep/software-testing-p01] More than a third of this cost could be avoided if better software testing was performed.
[src:great-expectations-deep/software-testing-p01] Outsourcing software testing because of costs is very common, with China, the Philippines, India and Pakistan being preferred destinations.
[src:great-expectations-deep/software-testing-p01] Myers initially introduced the separation of debugging from testing in 1979.
[src:great-expectations-deep/software-testing-p01] Although his attention was on breakage testing ("A successful test case is one that detects an as-yet undiscovered error."), it illustrated the desire of the software engineering community to separate fundamental development activities, such as debugging, from that of verification.
[src:great-expectations-deep/software-testing-p01] Software testing typically includes handling software bugs – a defect in the code that causes an undesirable result.
[src:great-expectations-deep/software-testing-p01] Bugs generally slow testing progress and involve programmer assistance to debug and fix.
[src:great-expectations-deep/software-testing-p01] For example, a defect in dead code will not be considered a failure.
[src:great-expectations-deep/software-testing-p01] A defect that does not cause failure at one point in time may lead to failure later due to environmental changes.
[src:great-expectations-deep/software-testing-p01] Examples of environment change include running on new computer hardware, changes in data, and interacting with different software.
[src:great-expectations-deep/software-testing-p01] Software testing is typically goal driven.
[src:great-expectations-deep/software-testing-p01] A single defect may result in multiple failure symptoms.
[src:great-expectations-deep/software-testing-p01] Software testing may involve a Requirements gap – omission from the design for a requirement.
[src:great-expectations-deep/software-testing-p01] Requirement gaps can often be non-functional requirements such as testability, scalability, maintainability, performance, and security.
[src:great-expectations-deep/software-testing-p01] A fundamental limitation of software testing is that testing under *all* combinations of inputs and preconditions (initial state) is not feasible, even with a simple product.
[src:great-expectations-deep/software-testing-p01] Defects that manifest in unusual conditions are difficult to find in testing.
[src:great-expectations-deep/software-testing-p01] Also, non-functional dimensions of quality (how it is supposed to *be* versus what it is supposed to *do*) – usability, scalability, performance, compatibility, and reliability – can be subjective; something that constitutes sufficient value to one person may not to another.
[src:great-expectations-deep/software-testing-p01] Although testing for every possible input is not feasible, testing can use combinatorics to maximize coverage while minimizing tests.
[src:great-expectations-deep/software-testing-p01] Test automation is the use of software (separate from the software being tested) for controlling the execution of tests and comparing actual outcome with predicted.
[src:great-expectations-deep/software-testing-p01] Test automation supports testing the system under test (SUT) without manual interaction which can lead to faster test execution and testing more often.
[src:great-expectations-deep/software-testing-p01] Test automation is a key aspect of continuous testing and often for continuous integration and continuous delivery (CI/CD).
[src:great-expectations-deep/software-testing-p01] Software testing can be categorized into levels based on how much of the software system is the focus of a test.
[src:great-expectations-deep/software-testing-p01] Unit testing, a.k.a. component or module testing, is a form of software testing by which isolated source code is tested to validate expected behavior.
[src:great-expectations-deep/software-testing-p01] Integration testing is a form of software testing in which multiple software components, modules, or services are tested together to verify they work as expected when combined.
[src:great-expectations-deep/software-testing-p01] The focus is on testing the interactions and data exchange between integrated parts, rather than testing components in isolation.
[src:great-expectations-deep/software-testing-p01] System testing, a.k.a. end-to-end (E2E) testing, is testing conducted on a complete software system.
[src:great-expectations-deep/software-testing-p01] There are many approaches to software testing.
[src:great-expectations-deep/software-testing-p01] Reviews, walkthroughs, or inspections are referred to as static testing, whereas executing programmed code with a given set of test cases is referred to as dynamic testing.
[src:great-expectations-deep/software-testing-p01] Static testing is often implicit, like proofreading, plus when programming tools/text editors check source code structure or compilers (precompilers) check syntax and data flow as static program analysis.
[src:great-expectations-deep/software-testing-p01] Dynamic testing takes place when the program itself is run.
[src:great-expectations-deep/software-testing-p01] Dynamic testing may begin before the program is 100% complete in order to test particular sections of code and are applied to discrete functions or modules.
[src:great-expectations-deep/software-testing-p01] Typical techniques for these are either using stubs/drivers or execution from a debugger environment.
[src:great-expectations-deep/software-testing-p01] Static testing involves verification, whereas dynamic testing also involves validation.
[src:great-expectations-deep/software-testing-p01] Passive testing means verifying the system's behavior without any interaction with the software product.
[src:great-expectations-deep/software-testing-p01] Contrary to active testing, testers do not provide any test data but look at system logs and traces.
[src:great-expectations-deep/software-testing-p01] They mine for patterns and specific behavior in order to make some kind of decisions.
[src:great-expectations-deep/software-testing-p01] This is related to offline runtime verification and log analysis.
[src:great-expectations-deep/software-testing-p01] Exploratory testing is an approach to software testing that is concisely described as simultaneous learning, test design and test execution.
[src:great-expectations-deep/software-testing-p01] Software testing can often be divided into white-box and black-box.
[src:great-expectations-deep/software-testing-p01] These two approaches are used to describe the point of view that the tester takes when designing test cases.
[src:great-expectations-deep/software-testing-p01] A hybrid approach called grey-box that includes aspects of both boxes may also be applied to software testing methodology.
[src:great-expectations-deep/software-testing-p01] White-box testing (also known as clear box testing, glass box testing, transparent box testing, and structural testing) verifies the internal structures or workings of a program, as opposed to the functionality exposed to the end-user.
[src:great-expectations-deep/software-testing-p01] In white-box testing, an internal perspective of the system (the source code), as well as programming skills are used to design test cases.
[src:great-expectations-deep/software-testing-p01] The tester chooses inputs to exercise paths through the code and determines the appropriate outputs.
[src:great-expectations-deep/software-testing-p01] This is analogous to testing nodes in a circuit, e.g., in-circuit testing (ICT).
[src:great-expectations-deep/software-testing-p01] While white-box testing can be applied at the unit, integration, and system levels of the software testing process, it is usually done at the unit level.
[src:great-expectations-deep/software-testing-p01] It can test paths within a unit, paths between units during integration, and between subsystems during a system–level test.
[src:great-expectations-deep/software-testing-p01] Though this method of test design can uncover many errors or problems, it might not detect unimplemented parts of the specification or missing requirements.
[src:great-expectations-deep/software-testing-p01] Code coverage tools can evaluate the completeness of a test suite that was created with any method, including black-box testing.
[src:great-expectations-deep/software-testing-p01] This allows the software team to examine parts of a system that are rarely tested and ensures that the most important function points have been tested.
[src:great-expectations-deep/software-testing-p01] 100% statement coverage ensures that all code paths or branches (in terms of control flow) are executed at least once.
[src:great-expectations-deep/software-testing-p01] This is helpful in ensuring correct functionality, but not sufficient since the same code may process different inputs correctly or incorrectly.
[src:great-expectations-deep/software-testing-p01] Black-box testing (also known as functional testing) describes designing test cases without knowledge of the implementation, without reading the source code.
[src:great-expectations-deep/software-testing-p01] The testers are only aware of what the software is supposed to do, not how it does it.
[src:great-expectations-deep/software-testing-p01] Black-box testing methods include: equivalence partitioning, boundary value analysis, all-pairs testing, state transition tables, decision table testing, fuzz testing, model-based testing, use case testing, exploratory testing, and specification-based testing.
[src:great-expectations-deep/software-testing-p01] Specification-based testing aims to test the functionality of software according to the applicable requirements.
[src:great-expectations-deep/software-testing-p01] This level of testing usually requires thorough test cases to be provided to the tester, who then can simply verify that for a given input, the output value (or behavior), either "is" or "is not" the same as the expected value specified in the test case.
[src:great-expectations-deep/software-testing-p01] Test cases are built around specifications and requirements, i.e., what the application is supposed to do.
[src:great-expectations-deep/software-testing-p01] It uses external descriptions of the software, including specifications, requirements, and designs, to derive test cases.
[src:great-expectations-deep/software-testing-p01] These tests can be functional or non-functional, though usually functional.
[src:great-expectations-deep/software-testing-p01] Specification-based testing may be necessary to assure correct functionality, but it is insufficient to guard against complex or high-risk situations.
[src:great-expectations-deep/software-testing-p01] Black box testing can be used to any level of testing although usually not at the unit level.
[src:great-expectations-deep/software-testing-p01] Component interface testing is a variation of black-box testing, with the focus on the data values beyond just the related actions of a subsystem component.
[src:great-expectations-deep/software-testing-p01] The practice of component interface testing can be used to check the handling of data passed between various units, or subsystem components, beyond full integration testing between those units.
[src:great-expectations-deep/software-testing-p01] The data being passed can be considered as "message packets" and the range or data types can be checked for data generated from one unit and tested for validity before being passed into another unit.
[src:great-expectations-deep/software-testing-p01] One option for interface testing is to keep a separate log file of data items being passed, often with a timestamp logged to allow analysis of thousands of cases of data passed between units for days or weeks.
[src:great-expectations-deep/software-testing-p01] Tests can include checking the handling of some extreme data values while other interface variables are passed as normal values.
[src:great-expectations-deep/software-testing-p01] Unusual data values in an interface can help explain unexpected performance in the next unit.
[src:great-expectations-deep/software-testing-p01] The aim of visual testing is to provide developers with the ability to examine what was happening at the point of software failure by presenting the data in such a way that the developer can easily find the information he or she requires, and the information is expressed clearly.
[src:great-expectations-deep/software-testing-p01] At the core of visual testing is the idea that showing someone a problem (or a test failure), rather than just describing it, greatly increases clarity and understanding.
[src:great-expectations-deep/software-testing-p01] Visual testing, therefore, requires the recording of the entire test process – capturing everything that occurs on the test system in video format.
[src:great-expectations-deep/software-testing-p01] Output videos are supplemented by real-time tester input via picture-in-a-picture webcam and audio commentary from microphones.
[src:great-expectations-deep/software-testing-p01] Visual testing provides a number of advantages.
[src:great-expectations-deep/software-testing-p01] The quality of communication is increased drastically because testers can show the problem (and the events leading up to it) to the developer as opposed to just describing it, and the need to replicate test failures will cease to exist in many cases.
[src:great-expectations-deep/software-testing-p01] The developer will have all the evidence he or she requires of a test failure and can instead focus on the cause of the fault and how it should be fixed.
[src:great-expectations-deep/software-testing-p01] Ad hoc testing and exploratory testing are important methodologies for checking software integrity because they require less preparation time to implement, while the important bugs can be found quickly.
[src:great-expectations-deep/software-testing-p01] In ad hoc testing, where testing takes place in an improvised impromptu way, the ability of the tester(s) to base testing off documented methods and then improvise variations of those tests can result in a more rigorous examination of defect fixes.
[src:great-expectations-deep/software-testing-p01] However, unless strict documentation of the procedures is maintained, one of the limits of ad hoc testing is lack of repeatability.
[src:great-expectations-deep/software-testing-p01] Grey-box testing (American spelling: gray-box testing) involves using knowledge of internal data structures and algorithms for purposes of designing tests while executing those tests at the user, or black-box level.
[src:great-expectations-deep/software-testing-p01] The tester will often have access to both "the source code and the executable binary." Grey-box testing may also include reverse engineering (using dynamic code analysis) to determine, for instance, boundary values or error messages.
[src:great-expectations-deep/software-testing-p01] Manipulating input data and formatting output do not qualify as grey-box, as the input and output are clearly outside of the "black box" that we are calling the system under test.
[src:great-expectations-deep/software-testing-p01] This distinction is particularly important when conducting integration testing between two modules of code written by two different developers, where only the interfaces are exposed for the test.
[src:great-expectations-deep/software-testing-p01] By knowing the underlying concepts of how the software works, the tester makes better-informed testing choices while testing the software from outside.
[src:great-expectations-deep/software-testing-p01] Typically, a grey-box tester will be permitted to set up an isolated testing environment with activities, such as seeding a database.
[src:great-expectations-deep/software-testing-p01] The tester can observe the state of the product being tested after performing certain actions such as executing SQL statements against the database and then executing queries to ensure that the expected changes have been reflected.
[src:great-expectations-deep/software-testing-p01] Grey-box testing implements intelligent test scenarios based on limited information.
[src:great-expectations-deep/software-testing-p01] This will particularly apply to data type handling, exception handling, and so on.
[src:great-expectations-deep/software-testing-p01] With the concept of grey-box testing, this "arbitrary distinction" between black- and white-box testing has faded somewhat.
[src:great-expectations-deep/software-testing-p01] Installation testing is a type of software testing that verifies that users can successfully install and set up software in its intended environments (e.g., operating systems, computer hardware).
[src:great-expectations-deep/software-testing-p01] Most software systems have installation procedures that are needed before they can be used for their main purpose.
[src:great-expectations-deep/software-testing-p01] Installation testing focuses on these procedures and whether they're sufficient for achieving an installed, usable software system.
[src:great-expectations-deep/software-testing-p01] Procedures of this kind may involve full or partial upgrades, and install/uninstall processes.
[src:great-expectations-deep/software-testing-p01] For example, in the case of a lack of backward compatibility, this can occur because the programmers develop and test software only on the latest version of the target environment, which not all users may be running.
[src:great-expectations-deep/software-testing-p01] This results in the unintended consequence that the latest work may not function on earlier versions of the target environment, or on older hardware that earlier versions of the target environment were capable of using.
[src:great-expectations-deep/software-testing-p01] Sometimes such issues can be fixed by proactively abstracting operating system functionality into a separate program module or library.
[src:great-expectations-deep/software-testing-p01] Sanity testing determines whether it is reasonable to proceed with further testing.
[src:great-expectations-deep/software-testing-p01] Smoke testing consists of minimal attempts to operate the software, designed to determine whether there are any basic problems that will prevent it from working at all.
[src:great-expectations-deep/software-testing-p01] Such tests can be used as build verification test.
[src:great-expectations-deep/software-testing-p01] Regression testing focuses on finding defects after a major code change has occurred.
[src:great-expectations-deep/software-testing-p01] Specifically, it seeks to uncover software regressions, as degraded or lost features, including old bugs that have come back.
[src:great-expectations-deep/software-testing-p01] Such regressions occur whenever software functionality that was previously working correctly, stops working as intended.
[src:great-expectations-deep/software-testing-p01] Typically, regressions occur as an unintended consequence of program changes, when the newly developed part of the software collides with the previously existing code.
[src:great-expectations-deep/software-testing-p01] Common methods of regression testing include re-running previous sets of test cases and checking whether previously fixed faults have re-emerged.
[src:great-expectations-deep/software-testing-p01] The depth of testing depends on the phase in the release process and the risk of the added features.
[src:great-expectations-deep/software-testing-p01] They can either be complete, for changes added late in the release or deemed to be risky, or be very shallow, consisting of positive tests on each feature, if the changes are early in the release or deemed to be of low risk.
[src:great-expectations-deep/software-testing-p01] Acceptance testing is system-level testing to ensure the software meets customer expectations.
[src:great-expectations-deep/software-testing-p01] Acceptance testing may be performed at the end or in the middle of a project, including after each completed user story in an agile project.
[src:great-expectations-deep/software-testing-p01] Tests are frequently grouped into these levels by where they are performed in the software development process, or by the level of specificity of the test.
[src:great-expectations-deep/software-testing-p01] Sometimes, UAT is performed by the customer, in their environment and on their own hardware.
[src:great-expectations-deep/software-testing-p01] OAT is used to conduct operational readiness (prerelease) of a product, service or system as part of a quality management system.
[src:great-expectations-deep/software-testing-p01] OAT is a common type of non-functional software testing, used mainly in software development and software maintenance projects.
[src:great-expectations-deep/software-testing-p01] This type of testing focuses on the operational readiness of the system to be supported, or to become part of the production environment.
[src:great-expectations-deep/software-testing-p01] Hence, it is also known as operational readiness testing (ORT) or operations readiness and assurance (OR&A) testing.
[src:great-expectations-deep/software-testing-p01] Functional testing within OAT is limited to those tests that are required to verify the *non-functional* aspects of the system.
[src:great-expectations-deep/software-testing-p01] In addition, the software testing should ensure that the portability of the system, as well as working as expected, does not also damage or partially corrupt its operating environment or cause other processes within that environment to become inoperative.
[src:great-expectations-deep/software-testing-p01] Contractual acceptance testing is performed based on the contract's acceptance criteria defined during the agreement of the contract, while regulatory acceptance testing is performed based on the relevant regulations to the software product.
[src:great-expectations-deep/software-testing-p01] Both of these two tests can be performed by users or independent testers.
[src:great-expectations-deep/software-testing-p01] Regulation acceptance testing sometimes involves the regulatory agencies auditing the test results.
[src:great-expectations-deep/software-testing-p01] Alpha testing is simulated or actual operational testing by potential users/customers or an independent test team at the developers' site.
[src:great-expectations-deep/software-testing-p01] Alpha testing is often employed for off-the-shelf software as a form of internal acceptance testing before the software goes to beta testing.
[src:great-expectations-deep/software-testing-p01] Beta testing comes after alpha testing and can be considered a form of external user acceptance testing.
[src:great-expectations-deep/software-testing-p01] Versions of the software, known as beta versions, are released to a limited audience outside of the programming team known as beta testers.
[src:great-expectations-deep/software-testing-p01] The software is released to groups of people so that further testing can ensure the product has few faults or bugs.
[src:great-expectations-deep/software-testing-p01] Beta versions can be made available to the open public to increase the feedback field to a maximal number of future users and to deliver value earlier, for an extended or even indefinite period of time (perpetual beta).
[src:great-expectations-deep/software-testing-p01] Functional testing refers to activities that verify a specific action or function of the code.
[src:great-expectations-deep/software-testing-p01] These are usually found in the code requirements documentation, although some development methodologies work from use cases or user stories.
[src:great-expectations-deep/software-testing-p01] Non-functional testing refers to aspects of the software that may not be related to a specific function or user action, such as scalability or other performance, behavior under certain constraints, or security.
[src:great-expectations-deep/software-testing-p01] Testing will determine the breaking point, the point at which extremes of scalability or performance leads to unstable execution.
[src:great-expectations-deep/software-testing-p01] Non-functional requirements tend to be those that reflect the quality of the product, particularly in the context of the suitability perspective of its users.
[src:great-expectations-deep/software-testing-p01] Continuous testing is the process of executing automated tests as part of the software delivery pipeline to obtain immediate feedback on the business risks associated with a software release candidate.
[src:great-expectations-deep/software-testing-p01] Continuous testing includes the validation of both functional requirements and non-functional requirements; the scope of testing extends from validating bottom-up requirements or user stories to assessing the system requirements associated with overarching business goals.
[src:great-expectations-deep/software-testing-p01] Destructive testing attempts to cause the software or a sub-system to fail.
[src:great-expectations-deep/software-testing-p01] It verifies whether the software functions properly when it receives invalid or unexpected inputs, thereby assessing the robustness of input validation and error-management routines.
[src:great-expectations-deep/software-testing-p01] Software fault injection, in the form of fuzzing, is an example of failure testing.
[src:great-expectations-deep/software-testing-p01] Various commercial non-functional testing tools are linked from the software fault injection page; there are also numerous open-source and free software tools available that perform destructive testing.
[src:great-expectations-deep/software-testing-p01] Performance testing is generally executed to determine how a system or sub-system performs in terms of responsiveness and stability under a particular workload.
[src:great-expectations-deep/software-testing-p01] It can also serve to investigate, measure, validate or verify other quality attributes of the system, such as scalability, reliability and resource usage.
[src:great-expectations-deep/software-testing-p01] There is little agreement on what the specific goals of performance testing are.
[src:great-expectations-deep/software-testing-p01] The terms load testing, performance testing, scalability testing, and volume testing, are often used interchangeably.
[src:great-expectations-deep/software-testing-p01] Real-time software systems have strict timing constraints.
[src:great-expectations-deep/software-testing-p01] To test if timing constraints are met, real-time testing is used.
[src:great-expectations-deep/software-testing-p01] Usability testing is to check if the user interface is easy to use and understand.
[src:great-expectations-deep/software-testing-p01] It is concerned mainly with the use of the application.
[src:great-expectations-deep/software-testing-p01] This is not a kind of testing that can be automated; actual human users are needed, being monitored by skilled UI designers.
[src:great-expectations-deep/software-testing-p01] Usability testing can use structured models to check how well an interface works.
[src:great-expectations-deep/software-testing-p01] The Stanton, Theofanos, and Joshi (2015) model looks at user experience, and the Al-Sharafat and Qadoumi (2016) model is for expert evaluation, helping to assess usability in digital applications.
[src:great-expectations-deep/software-testing-p01] Accessibility testing is done to ensure that the software is accessible to persons with disabilities.
[src:great-expectations-deep/software-testing-p01] Security testing is essential for software that processes confidential data to prevent system intrusion by hackers.
[src:great-expectations-deep/software-testing-p01] Testing for internationalization and localization validates that the software can be used with different languages and geographic regions.
[src:great-expectations-deep/software-testing-p01] The process of pseudolocalization is used to test the ability of an application to be translated to another language, and make it easier to identify when the localization process may introduce new bugs into the product.
[src:great-expectations-deep/software-testing-p01] Globalization testing verifies that the software is adapted for a new culture, such as different currencies or time zones.
[src:great-expectations-deep/software-testing-p01] Actual translation to human languages must be tested, too.
[src:great-expectations-deep/software-testing-p01] Development testing is a software development process that involves the synchronized application of a broad spectrum of defect prevention and detection strategies in order to reduce software development risks, time, and costs.
[src:great-expectations-deep/software-testing-p01] It is performed by the software developer or engineer during the construction phase of the software development lifecycle.
[src:great-expectations-deep/software-testing-p01] Development testing aims to eliminate construction errors before code is promoted to other testing; this strategy is intended to increase the quality of the resulting software as well as the efficiency of the overall development process.
[src:great-expectations-deep/software-testing-p01] Depending on the organization's expectations for software development, development testing might include static code analysis, data flow analysis, metrics analysis, peer code reviews, unit testing, code coverage analysis, traceability, and other software testing practices.
[src:great-expectations-deep/software-testing-p01] A/B testing is a method of running a controlled experiment to determine if a proposed change is more effective than the current approach.
[src:great-expectations-deep/software-testing-p01] Customers are routed to either a current version (control) of a feature, or to a modified version (treatment) and data is collected to determine which version is better at achieving the desired outcome.
[src:great-expectations-deep/software-testing-p01] Concurrent or concurrency testing assesses the behaviour and performance of software and systems that use concurrent computing, generally under normal usage conditions.
[src:great-expectations-deep/software-testing-p01] Typical problems this type of testing will expose are deadlocks, race conditions and problems with shared memory/resource handling.
[src:great-expectations-deep/software-testing-p01] In software testing, conformance testing verifies that a product performs according to its specified standards.
[src:great-expectations-deep/software-testing-p01] Compilers, for instance, are extensively tested to determine whether they meet the recognized standard for that language.
[src:great-expectations-deep/software-testing-p01] For example, every output from a serialization function should be accepted by the corresponding deserialization function, and every output from a sort function should be a monotonically increasing list containing exactly the same elements as its input.
[src:great-expectations-deep/software-testing-p01] Property testing libraries allow the user to control the strategy by which random inputs are constructed, to ensure coverage of degenerate cases, or inputs featuring specific patterns that are needed to fully exercise aspects of the implementation under test.
[src:great-expectations-deep/software-testing-p01] Property testing is also sometimes known as "generative testing" or "QuickCheck testing" since it was introduced and popularized by the Haskell library QuickCheck.
[src:great-expectations-deep/software-testing-p01] Metamorphic testing (MT) is a property-based software testing technique, which can be an effective approach for addressing the test oracle problem and test case generation problem.
[src:great-expectations-deep/software-testing-p01] The test oracle problem is the difficulty of determining the expected outcomes of selected test cases or to determine whether the actual outputs agree with the expected outcomes.
[src:great-expectations-deep/software-testing-p01] VCR testing, also known as "playback testing" or "record/replay" testing, is a testing technique for increasing the reliability and speed of regression tests that involve a component that is slow or unreliable to communicate with, often a third-party API outside of the tester's control.
[src:great-expectations-deep/software-testing-p01] It involves making a recording ("cassette") of the system's interactions with the external component, and then replaying the recorded interactions as a substitute for communicating with the external system on subsequent runs of the test.
[src:great-expectations-deep/software-testing-p01] The technique was popularized in web development by the Ruby library vcr.
[src:great-expectations-deep/software-testing-p01] It is often used in the context of distributed systems, service-oriented software architectures, and microservices.
[src:great-expectations-deep/software-testing-p01] Since the early 2020s, artificial intelligence has increasingly been integrated into software testing workflows.
[src:great-expectations-deep/software-testing-p01] AI-driven testing methods automate the creation of test cases, dynamically adapt to changes, and leverage machine learning to identify high-risk areas of the codebase — an approach that enhances regression testing efficiency while expanding overall test coverage.
[src:great-expectations-deep/software-testing-p01] A key development is **self-healing test automation**, in which automated tests automatically detect and adapt to changes in a user interface without human intervention.
[src:great-expectations-deep/software-testing-p01] Studies of AI-driven test automation across over 3,600 grey literature sources identified self-healing test scripts as one of the most common AI solutions in practice.
[src:great-expectations-deep/software-testing-p01] A case study presented at the 2023 International Conference on Information Management and Technology (ICIMTech) found that integrating shift-left testing into an agile development methodology over one year measurably reduced the number of bugs reaching production.
[src:great-expectations-deep/software-testing-p01] In an organization, testers may be in a separate team from the rest of the software development team or they may be integrated into one team.
[src:great-expectations-deep/software-testing-p01] Software testing can also be performed by non-dedicated software testers.
[src:great-expectations-deep/software-testing-p01] In the 1980s, the term *software tester* started to be used to denote a separate profession.
[src:great-expectations-deep/software-testing-p01] Notable software testing roles and titles include: *test manager*, *test lead*, *test analyst*, *test designer*, *tester*, *automation developer*, and *test administrator*.
[src:great-expectations-deep/software-testing-p01] Organizations that develop software, perform testing differently, but there are common patterns.
[src:great-expectations-deep/software-testing-p01] In waterfall development, testing is generally performed after the code is completed, but before the product is shipped to the customer.
[src:great-expectations-deep/software-testing-p01] This practice often results in the testing phase being used as a project buffer to compensate for project delays, thereby compromising the time devoted to testing.
[src:great-expectations-deep/software-testing-p01] Some contend that the waterfall process allows for testing to start when the development project starts and to be a continuous process until the project finishes.
[src:great-expectations-deep/software-testing-p01] Agile software development commonly involves testing while the code is being written and organizing teams with both programmers and testers and with team members performing both programming and testing.
[src:great-expectations-deep/software-testing-p01] One agile practice, test-driven software development (TDD), is a way of unit testing such that unit-level testing is performed while writing the product code.
[src:great-expectations-deep/software-testing-p01] Test code is updated as new features are added and failure conditions are discovered (bugs fixed).
[src:great-expectations-deep/software-testing-p01] Commonly, the unit test code is maintained with the project code, integrated in the build process, and run on each build and as part of regression testing.
[src:great-expectations-deep/software-testing-p01] Goals of this continuous integration is to support development and reduce defects.
[src:great-expectations-deep/software-testing-p01] Even in organizations that separate teams by programming and testing functions, many often have the programmers perform unit testing.
[src:great-expectations-deep/software-testing-p01] The sample below is common for waterfall development.
[src:great-expectations-deep/software-testing-p01] The same activities are commonly found in other development models, but might be described differently.
[src:great-expectations-deep/software-testing-p02] The terms verification and validation are commonly used interchangeably in the industry; it is also common to see these two terms defined with contradictory definitions.
[src:great-expectations-deep/software-testing-p02] Verification is the process of evaluating a system or component to determine whether the products of a given development phase satisfy the conditions imposed at the start of that phase.
[src:great-expectations-deep/software-testing-p02] Validation is the process of evaluating a system or component during or at the end of the development process to determine whether it satisfies specified requirements.
[src:great-expectations-deep/software-testing-p02] Verification is confirmation by examination and through provision of objective evidence that specified requirements have been fulfilled.
[src:great-expectations-deep/software-testing-p02] Validation is confirmation by examination and through provision of objective evidence that the requirements for a specific intended use or application have been fulfilled.
[src:great-expectations-deep/software-testing-p02] The contradiction is caused by the use of the concepts of requirements and specified requirements but with different meanings.
[src:great-expectations-deep/software-testing-p02] In the case of IEEE standards, the specified requirements, mentioned in the definition of validation, are the set of problems, needs and wants of the stakeholders that the software must solve and satisfy.
[src:great-expectations-deep/software-testing-p02] Such requirements are documented in a Software Requirements Specification (SRS).
[src:great-expectations-deep/software-testing-p02] And, the products mentioned in the definition of verification, are the output artifacts of every phase of the software development process.
[src:great-expectations-deep/software-testing-p02] These products are, in fact, specifications such as Architectural Design Specification, Detailed Design Specification, etc.
[src:great-expectations-deep/software-testing-p02] The SRS is also a specification, but it cannot be verified (at least not in the sense used here – more on this subject below).
[src:great-expectations-deep/software-testing-p02] But, for the ISO 9000, the specified requirements are the set of specifications, as just mentioned above, that must be verified.
[src:great-expectations-deep/software-testing-p02] A specification, as previously explained, is the product of a software development process phase that receives another specification as input.
[src:great-expectations-deep/software-testing-p02] A specification is verified successfully when it correctly implements its input specification.
[src:great-expectations-deep/software-testing-p02] All the specifications can be verified except the SRS because it is the first one (it can be validated, though).
[src:great-expectations-deep/software-testing-p02] An example scenario be that the Design Specification must implement the SRS, and the Construction phase artifacts must implement the Design Specification.
[src:great-expectations-deep/software-testing-p02] So, when these words are defined in common terms, the apparent contradiction disappears.
[src:great-expectations-deep/software-testing-p02] Both the SRS and the software must be validated.
[src:great-expectations-deep/software-testing-p02] The SRS can be validated statically by consulting with the stakeholders.
[src:great-expectations-deep/software-testing-p02] Nevertheless, running some partial implementation of the software or a prototype of any kind (dynamic testing) and obtaining positive feedback from them, can further increase the certainty that the SRS is correctly formulated.
[src:great-expectations-deep/software-testing-p02] On the other hand, the software, as a final and running product (not its artifacts and documents, including the source code) must be validated dynamically with the stakeholders by executing the software and having them to try it.
[src:great-expectations-deep/software-testing-p02] Some might argue that, for SRS, the input is the words of stakeholders and, therefore, SRS validation is the same as SRS verification.
[src:great-expectations-deep/software-testing-p02] Thinking this way is not advisable as it only causes more confusion.
[src:great-expectations-deep/software-testing-p02] It is better to think of verification as a process involving a formal and technical input document.
[src:great-expectations-deep/software-testing-p02] In some organizations, software testing is part of a software quality assurance (SQA) process.
[src:great-expectations-deep/software-testing-p02] In SQA, software process specialists and auditors are concerned with the software development process rather than just the artifacts such as documentation, code and systems.
[src:great-expectations-deep/software-testing-p02] They examine and change the software engineering process itself to reduce the number of faults that end up in the delivered software: the so-called defect rate.
[src:great-expectations-deep/software-testing-p02] What constitutes an acceptable defect rate depends on the nature of the software; a flight simulator video game would have much higher defect tolerance than software for an actual airplane.
[src:great-expectations-deep/software-testing-p02] Although there are close links with SQA, testing departments often exist independently, and there may be no SQA function in some companies.
[src:great-expectations-deep/software-testing-p02] Software testing is an activity to investigate software under test in order to provide quality-related information to stakeholders.
[src:great-expectations-deep/software-testing-p02] By contrast, QA (quality assurance) is the implementation of policies and procedures intended to prevent defects from reaching customers.
[src:great-expectations-deep/software-testing-p02] Quality measures include such topics as correctness, completeness, security and ISO/IEC 9126 requirements such as capability, reliability, efficiency, portability, maintainability, compatibility, and usability.
[src:great-expectations-deep/software-testing-p02] There are a number of frequently used software metrics, or measures, which are used to assist in determining the state of the software or the adequacy of the testing.
[src:great-expectations-deep/software-testing-p02] A software testing process can produce several artifacts.
[src:great-expectations-deep/software-testing-p02] The actual artifacts produced are a factor of the software development model used, stakeholder and organisational needs.
[src:great-expectations-deep/software-testing-p02] A test plan is a document detailing the approach that will be taken for intended test activities.
[src:great-expectations-deep/software-testing-p02] The plan may include aspects such as objectives, scope, processes and procedures, personnel requirements, and contingency plans.
[src:great-expectations-deep/software-testing-p02] The test plan could come in the form of a single plan that includes all test types (like an acceptance or system test plan) and planning considerations, or it may be issued as a master test plan that provides an overview of more than one detailed test plan (a plan of a plan).
[src:great-expectations-deep/software-testing-p02] A test plan can be, in some cases, part of a wide "test strategy" which documents overall testing approaches, which may itself be a master test plan or even a separate artifact.
[src:great-expectations-deep/software-testing-p02] In software development, a traceability matrix (TM) is a document, usually in the form of a table, used to assist in determining the completeness of a relationship by correlating any two baselined documents using a many-to-many relationship comparison.
[src:great-expectations-deep/software-testing-p02] It is often used with high-level requirements (these often consist of marketing requirements) and detailed requirements of the product to the matching parts of high-level design, detailed design, test plan, and test cases.
[src:great-expectations-deep/software-testing-p02] A test case normally consists of a unique identifier, requirement references from a design specification, preconditions, events, a series of steps (also known as actions) to follow, input, output, expected result, and the actual result.
[src:great-expectations-deep/software-testing-p02] Clinically defined, a test case is an input and an expected result.
[src:great-expectations-deep/software-testing-p02] This can be as terse as "for condition x your derived result is y", although normally test cases describe in more detail the input scenario and what results might be expected.
[src:great-expectations-deep/software-testing-p02] It can occasionally be a series of steps (but often steps are contained in a separate test procedure that can be exercised against multiple test cases, as a matter of economy) but with one expected result or expected outcome.
[src:great-expectations-deep/software-testing-p02] The optional fields are a test case ID, test step, or order of execution number, related requirement(s), depth, test category, author, and check boxes for whether the test is automatable and has been automated.
[src:great-expectations-deep/software-testing-p02] Larger test cases may also contain prerequisite states or steps, and descriptions.
[src:great-expectations-deep/software-testing-p02] A test case should also contain a place for the actual result.
[src:great-expectations-deep/software-testing-p02] These steps can be stored in a word processor document, spreadsheet, database, or other common repositories.
[src:great-expectations-deep/software-testing-p02] In a database system, you may also be able to see past test results, who generated the results, and what system configuration was used to generate those results.
[src:great-expectations-deep/software-testing-p02] These past results would usually be stored in a separate table.
[src:great-expectations-deep/software-testing-p02] A test script is a procedure or programming code that replicates user actions.
[src:great-expectations-deep/software-testing-p02] Initially, the term was derived from the product of work created by automated regression test tools.
[src:great-expectations-deep/software-testing-p02] A test case will be a baseline to create test scripts using a tool or a program.
[src:great-expectations-deep/software-testing-p02] In software development, a test suite, less commonly known as a validation suite, is a collection of test cases that are intended to be used to test a software program to show that it has some specified set of behaviors.
[src:great-expectations-deep/software-testing-p02] A test suite often contains detailed instructions or goals for each collection of test cases and information on the system configuration to be used during testing.
[src:great-expectations-deep/software-testing-p02] A group of test cases may also contain prerequisite states or steps and descriptions of the following tests.
[src:great-expectations-deep/software-testing-p02] In most cases, multiple sets of values or data are used to test the same functionality of a particular feature.
[src:great-expectations-deep/software-testing-p02] All the test values and changeable environmental components are collected in separate files and stored as test data.
[src:great-expectations-deep/software-testing-p02] It is also useful to provide this data to the client and with the product or a project.
[src:great-expectations-deep/software-testing-p02] There are techniques to generate Test data.
[src:great-expectations-deep/software-testing-p02] The software, tools, samples of data input and output, and configurations are all referred to collectively as a test harness.
[src:great-expectations-deep/software-testing-p02] A test run is a collection of test cases or test suites that the user is executing and comparing the expected with the actual results.
[src:great-expectations-deep/software-testing-p02] Once complete, a report or all executed tests may be generated.
[src:great-expectations-deep/software-testing-p02] Several certification programs exist to support the professional aspirations of software testers and quality assurance specialists.
[src:great-expectations-deep/software-testing-p02] A few practitioners argue that the testing field is not ready for certification, as mentioned in the controversy section.
[src:great-expectations-deep/software-testing-p02] is so expensive relative to its value that it should be used sparingly.
[src:great-expectations-deep/software-testing-p02] The test automation then can be considered as a way to capture and implement the requirements.
[src:great-expectations-deep/software-testing-p02] As a general rule, the larger the system and the greater the complexity, the greater the ROI in test automation.
[src:great-expectations-deep/software-testing-p02] Also, the investment in tools and expertise can be amortized over multiple projects with the right level of knowledge sharing within an organization.
[src:great-expectations-deep/software-testing-p02] Significant opposition has formed out of the ranks of the context-driven school of software testing about the ISO 29119 standard.
[src:great-expectations-deep/software-testing-p02] Professional testing associations, such as the International Society for Software Testing, have attempted to have the standard withdrawn.
[src:great-expectations-deep/software-testing-p02] No certification now offered actually requires the applicant to show their ability to test software.
[src:great-expectations-deep/software-testing-p02] No certification is based on a widely accepted body of knowledge.
[src:great-expectations-deep/software-testing-p02] Certification itself cannot measure an individual's productivity, their skill, or practical knowledge, and cannot guarantee their competence, or professionalism as a tester.
[src:great-expectations-deep/software-testing-p02] There are opposing views on the applicability of studies used to show the relative expense of fixing defects depending on their introduction and detection.
